case_name: Nizamat Co-operative Credit Societies v. Raja Nandial

facts.text: Appeal under article 374 4 of the Constitution from a judgment and decree of the High Court of Hyderabad dated 24th Aban 1356 F., in Civil Appeal No. 374/4 of 1356 F.

facts.text: Appeal arises out of execution proceedings of a decree passed by an arbitrator under the Co-operative Credit Societies Act.

anchor.surface_text: ered by MAHAJAN J.--This appeal arises out of execution proceed- ings of a decree passed by an arbitrator under the Co-opera- tive Credit Societies Act.

facts.text: Appeal was presented to the Judicial Committee of the State and is now before us under article 374 4 of the Constitution.

anchor.surface_text: The appeal was presented to the Judicial Committee of the State and is number before us under article 374  4  of the Constitution.

facts.text: Raja Nandial was a member of the decree-holder society and was also its debtor.

anchor.surface_text: Raja Nandial was a member of the decree-holder society and was also its debtor.

facts.text: A dispute arose between Raja Nandial and the society and was referred to arbitration under the rules governing such societies.

anchor.surface_text: A dispute arose between him and the society and under the rules governing such societies the matter was referred to arbitration.

facts.text: Arbitrator passed a decree against Raja Nandial on 19th Meher 1352 F. for Rs. 8,100 payable in equal six monthly instalments with six per cent interest, first instalment payable at the end of Azur 1353 F.

anchor.surface_text: The arbitrator on the 19th Meher 1352 F., passed a decree against him in the sum of Rs. 8,100 payable in equal six monthly instalments with six per cent. interest, the first instalment being payable at the end of Azur 1353 F.

facts.text: On 2nd Dai 1353 F., decree sent for execution to civil court on certificate issued by Moulvi Mohammed Hasan, Madadgar Nazim under section 42 clause d of Cooperative Societies Act. Amount: Rs. 8,100 principal and Rs. 6669-0 interest.

anchor.surface_text: On the 2nd Dai 1353 F., under the provisions of section 42, clause  d , of the Co-opera- tive Societies Act the decree was sent for execution to the civil companyrt on a certificate issued under the signature of one Moulvi Mohammed Hasan, Madadgar Nazim. The amount recoverable was stated as Rs. 8,100 principal and Rs. 6669-0 interest.

facts.text: On the same day, decree-holder presented application for execution to Civil Court Balda claiming Rs. 10,339-14-9 due to default in first instalment of Azur 1353 F making whole amount recoverable, prayed attachment of property.

anchor.surface_text: On the same day the decree-holder present- ed an application for execution of the decree to the Civil Court, Balda. claiming recovery of Rs. 10,339-14-9. It was alleged that as default had been companymitted in the payment of the first instalment due in the month of Azur 1353 F, the whole decretal amount had become recoverable. It was prayed that the property detailed in the application be attached.

facts.text: On 3rd Dai 1353 F., judgment debtor deposited Rs. 1,000 towards first instalment in Office of Registrar of Co-operative Societies and expressed willingness to deposit further amount due.

anchor.surface_text: On 3rd Dai 1353 F., i.e., a day after the presentation of the application for execution, the judgment debtor deposited a sum of Rs. 1,000 towards the first instalment in the Office of the Registrar of Co-operative Societies and ex- pressed his will lingness to deposit any further amount that may be due towards that instalment.

facts.text: Nazim's office stated that due to default in first instalment whole decree due and Rs. 1,000 would not be accepted.

anchor.surface_text: The Nazims office stated in reply that as he had companymitted default in the payment of the first instalment the whole decree had become due and the amount of Rs. 1,000 companyld number be accepted.

facts.text: On 5th Dai 1353 F., letter issued by Mohammed Aihsan, Assistant Madadgar Nazim, to Civil Court Balda stating Rs. 1,034 deposited and execution proceedings should be stayed or adjourned.

anchor.surface_text: Subsequentiy, however, on the 5th Dai 1353 F, a letter was issued by one Mohammed Aihsan, Assistant Madadgar Nazim, to the Civil Court, Balda, saying that Rs. 1,034 had been deposited in the Office of the Nizamat Co operative Credit Societies and therefore the proceedings in execution should be stayed or adjourned.

facts.text: Decree-holder objected that Registrar had no jurisdiction to stay execution as he was not an executing court.

anchor.surface_text: On receipt of the letter in the civil companyrt, the decree-holder raised an objection that the Registrar had numberjurisdiction to stay execution of the decree as he was number an executing companyrt.

facts.text: Executing court overruled objection and held Registrar retained power under section 42 to stay execution even after issuing certificate; stayed proceedings.

anchor.surface_text: This objection was overruled by the companyrt and it was held that under the provi- sions of section 42 of the Co-operative Credit Societies Act the Registrar retained the power of staying execution of the award decree even after the issue of a certificate by him. In the result the execution proceedings were stayed.

facts.text: Appeal taken to Sadar Adalat against the order staying execution.

anchor.surface_text: Against this order an appeal was taken to the Sadar Adalat.

facts.text: Sadar Adalat allowed appeal partially: no execution to extent of payment made but executable for future instalments as due; default clause condoned by deposit.

anchor.surface_text: The Sadar Adalat allowed the appeal partially and held that to the extent of the payment made the decree companyld number be executed but it companyld be executed with respect to future instalments as and when they would fall due. It further found that the default clause in the decree must be taken to have been companydoned by the deposit of the first instalment in the office of the Registrar.

facts.text: Decree-holder preferred second appeal to High Court without material success.

anchor.surface_text: The decree-holder preferred a second appeal to the High Court but without any material success.

facts.text: High Court held there was default in first instalment and decree-holder had right to execute whole decree.

anchor.surface_text: The High Court held that there had been a default in the payment of the first instalment and the decree-holder had thus a right to execute the whole decree and that neither the Registrar number the execut- ing companyrt companyld deprive the decree-holder of that right.

facts.text: High Court held judgment-debtor's contention that certificate bad as issued by Madadgar Nazim was negatived; Madadgar had delegated powers, defect cured by fresh certificate by Nazim.

anchor.surface_text: The companytention of the judgment-debtor that the cer- tificate was bad as having been issued by a Madadgar Nazim was negatived. It was held that the Madadgar Nazim had delegated powers in this respect and that the defect, if any, stood cured by a fresh certificate signed by the Nazim himself.

facts.text: High Court maintained decision of executing court adjourning execution proceedings.

anchor.surface_text: The result was that with these findings the deci- sion of the executing companyrt adjourning the execution pro- ceedings was maintained.

facts.text: Supreme Court allowed the appeal, set aside decisions of all three courts below, directed executing court to proceed with execution from stage interfered by Registrar's letter.

anchor.surface_text: The result therefore is that this appeal is allowed, the decisions of all the three companyrts below are set aside and the executing companyrt is directed to proceed with the execu- tion of the decree from the stage at which it was interfered with by the letter received from the office of the Regis- trar.

holdings.text: The Registrar under section 42, clause (d) of the Co-operative Credit Societies Act is not constituted as an executing court and no powers in the matter of execution of the award decree have been conferred upon him; his only jurisdiction is to issue a certificate for enforcement through a civil court or revenue court.

anchor.surface_text: The language employed in this section does number place the Registrar on the same pedestal as a companyrt passing the decree under the Civil Procedure Code. Under the Code a civil companyrt passing a decree is also the companyrt executing the decree. It has a dual capacity,  1  of the companyrt passing the decree, and  2  of the executing companyrt. The Registrar, it appears, has the first capacity of a civil companyrt but he has number been placed in the matter of execution in the same capacity as a civil companyrt passing a decree. The only jurisdiction companyferred on the Registrar is that he can issue a certificate and on that certificate he can send a decree either to the civil companyrt or to a revenue officer. It may be that after issuing a certificate he may be entitled to cancel the certificate or issue another, or he may by with- drawing the certificate withdraw execution from a civil companyrt and send it to a revenue companyrt and vice versa. On the plain words of the section it cannot be held that the Regis- trar has been companystituted an executing companyrt or that any powers in the matter of the execution of the award decree have been companyferred upon him.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Plain language of section 42(d) limits Registrar to certification for enforcement by other courts; lacks dual capacity of courts under CPC.

holdings.text: In view of the construction of section 42(d), the Registrar cannot intervene during execution proceedings pending in a civil court on the basis of the certificate granted by him.

anchor.surface_text: The question that arises for consideration is whether in view of this construction of the section it was open to the Registrar to intervene during execution proceedings that were pending in a civil court on the basis of the certificate granted by him. In order to determine this point it is necessary to see precisely what the Registrar actually did in this case.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Once certificate issued and execution pending, Registrar's role ends; intervention exceeds statutory authority.

holdings.text: The Registrar had no jurisdiction to accept the first instalment and direct stay of execution after default and initiation of execution proceedings; this was a trespass on the duties of the executing court.
holdings.reasoning_summary: Payment can only be made in executing court; Registrar lacks execution jurisdiction post-certification.

holdings.text: The Registrar could not alter or amend the decree passed by the arbitrator at this stage.
holdings.reasoning_summary: No statutory power to amend post-arbitration award and certification.

holdings.text: The analogy of decisions under the Civil Procedure Code regarding retention of execution jurisdiction by the court passing the decree is not applicable to the Registrar under the Co-operative Societies Act.

anchor.surface_text: Under the Code a civil companyrt passing a decree is also the companyrt executing the decree. It has a dual capacity,  1  of the companyrt passing the decree, and  2  of the executing companyrt. The Registrar, it appears, has the first capacity of a civil companyrt but he has number been placed in the matter of execution in the same capacity as a civil companyrt passing a decree.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Statutory language distinguishes Registrar's limited role from CPC courts' dual capacity.

holdings.text: The requisition of the Registrar to stop execution proceedings and acceptance of instalment were in excess of jurisdiction conferred and the executing court was entitled to ignore it.

anchor.surface_text: That being so, in our opinion, the requisition of the Registrar to the executing companyrt to stop execution proceedings and his act in accepting the first instalment were in excess of the jurisdiction companyferred on him and the executing companyrt was entitled to ignore it.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Registrar's actions exceed certification power; executing court independent.

holdings.text: It is unnecessary to consider whether there was no proper certificate as a fresh certificate was issued by the Nazim curing any defect.
holdings.reasoning_summary: Fresh certificate by competent authority renders issue moot.
